record.dcterms:title: Peck, Arthur World War I Student File
record.dcterms:creator: Peck, Arthur Edward, 1886-1960
record.dcterms:description: Arthur Edward Peck was born on December 4, 1886 in Blossburg, PA. He was a student at the Bloomsburg State Normal School from 1906-1907. While in France during the war, Peck was enrolled in the Heavy Artillery School and served with a supply unit. Following the war he worked in New York and Massachusetts and during World War II was stationed at Fort Monroe, VA. Peck died on September 27, 1960 and is buried in Blossburg.

record.dcterms:title: Maypole dance with lords and ladies
record.dcterms:creator: Unknown
record.dcterms:description: Students playing lords and ladies sit on the lawn and watch the maypole dance. In the background, Andrew W. Mellon's greenhouse is visible to the left and Lindsay House to the right. The 1923 May Day pageant featured a number of episodes from varying cultures and historical traditions. Part I, titled the "Birth of May Day" included dances by the allegorical figures of Night, Dawn, the Sun, and Spring among others. Part II centered on the "Coronation of the May Queen," senior Marion Jobson, and Part III, titled "Entertainment of the Queen," featured a wizard, a Roman Spring procession, an Egyptian episode, a Grecian episode, a Normandy folk dance, an English folk dance, a Japanese episode, “poses from old prints,” and a cherry blossom dance. The pageant was written by Mary Brown ‘23 and directed by Vanda E. Kerst with assistance from Mary Jane Paul. Dancing was choreographed by Marion Gifford, and the orchestra director was J. Vic O’Brien.

record.dcterms:title: Snow White and the dwarves
record.dcterms:creator: Unknown
record.dcterms:description: Christine Griggs '27, who played Snow White, is carried by the dwarves and others as the Prince (Virginia Thompson, special student) bows his head. The seven dwarves were played by Rose Bloom, Annetta Dunbar, Katherine Letterman, Margaret McEwen, Ruth McKeever, Violet Musselman, and Inez Wallis. The 1925 May Day festival, "A Day in Fairyland," featured scenes from classic fairy tales along with the traditional coronation and maypole dance. Part I, "The Coming of Day," included dances by students portraying fairies, the Day, Rain, Sun, and Rainbow as well as Puck, flowers, and elves. Part II focused on the crowning of the Fairy Queen (May Queen) Mary Shane '25 and a maypole dance by the senior class. Part III consisted of three acts from classic fairy tales: first Snow White, then the Story of the Golden Goose, and finally Cinderella. Part IV, "The Close of Day," featured the dances of Evening, the Sandman, Moonlight, the Stars, and Night followed by the recessional. The pageant was directed by Vanda Kerst and written by Helen Ahlers '25, Marian Frank '25, and Harriet Thomas. Thomas was a member of the class of 1928 but passed away on July 25, 1925.

record.dcterms:title: Crowning of Maid Marian
record.dcterms:creator: Unknown
record.dcterms:description: Ruth Fite as Robin Hood crowns May Queen Mary Milne as Maid Marian under the maypole. The 1939 "May Day Revels and Play," set in Sevenoaks Village in 1572, was described in the program as follows: "On the first of May the villagers, having chosen their Queen, go into the woods to gather boughs and flowers. Then with merry shouts and blowing of horns they return--singing "Summer is a-coming in"--and dance on the green. Queen Elizabeth, making a royal progress through her realm, arrives with her courtiers and attendants at Sevenoaks village and watches the May revels of the country folk. The May Queen, representing Maid Marian and attended by the village youth who has been chosen to be Robin Hood, rides to the common with her maids, the merry men of the greenwood, and the girls who deck her way with flowers. She is crowned by Robin Hood. In her honor and in honor of Queen Elizabeth, many country dances are performed and the play of St. George and the Dragon, symbolic of the death of Winter and the coming of Spring, is presented. Hobby horses, stilt walkers, tumblers, jesters engage in merry pastimes on the green."

The Sanitarium was a health resort primarily catering to wealthy patrons employing health priciples based on the teaching of the Seventh-day Adventist Church. Sanitarium practices focused on diet and exercise, as well as a variety of other practices including massage, water therapy, electro-therapy, rest, exposure to open air, colonics, and more. On site laboratories provided patients with detailed diet plans and analysis of patients health functions. This volume outlines in detail the principles and practices of the Sanitarium, as well as the buildings and grounds where patients resided and received treatments.

record.dcterms:title: Page, Walter World War I Student File
record.dcterms:creator: Page, Henry
Morning Press
record.dcterms:description: Walter Page was born November 27, 1894 in Richfield, PA, the son of Henry and Savilla Page. He was a student at the Bloomsburg State Normal School from 1915-1917. In June 1917, Page passed entrance examinations for the military, and was accepted as a musician in the infantry and went to Fort Slocum, NY. He was sent over to France where he was severely wounded on July 18, 1918, and reported as missing in action on August 12. Page's family recieved notification on March 5, 1919 that their son had died as a result of those injuries. He is remembered in the World War I Memorial Pinery.

record.dcterms:title: Ye Coffee House, 1760
record.dcterms:creator: Carpenter, Samuel, 1649-1714
Castner, Samuel, Jr., 1843-1929
record.dcterms:description: The first public-house designated as a 'coffee house' was built in Penn's time by Samuel Carpenter, on the east side of Front Street, probably above Walnut Street. That it was the first of its kind, the only one, in fact, for some years, seems to be established beyond doubt. It was always alluded to in old times as 'ye Coffee-House'. Samuel Carpenter owned also the Globe Inn, which was separated from the coffee house by a public stairway running down from Front Street to Water, and, it is supposed, to 'Carpenter's wharf'. The Coffee-House was a great place in those days; it was there the ship captains and merchants congregated to discuss the commercial and political news.. Source: History of Philadelphia, 1609-1884, Volume 2, page #982, by Scharf and Westcott.
